<CaseStudy slug="product-generation-pipeline">
  <p class="lead reveal">Manually producing a catalog of digital products — laying out interiors, designing covers, writing listings — doesn't scale. So I didn't make products; I made the machine that makes them. One spec in, a complete, print-ready product out.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">The engine</h2>
  <p class="reveal">A small set of parametric <code>Python</code> generators turns a single configuration into an entire product. Change a few parameters — region, theme, difficulty — and the same code produces a different, fully-formed SKU. From one script the pipeline scales to <strong>50+ variants</strong> without touching the layout logic again.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">What it generates, per product</h2>
  <ul class="reveal">
    <li><strong>Interiors</strong> — multi-page, print-spec PDFs generated programmatically, with front-matter and consistent typography.</li>
    <li><strong>Covers</strong> — parametric full-wrap cover PDFs computed to exact spine width and bleed, so they upload in one file with no manual design step.</li>
    <li><strong>Listings</strong> — formula-driven spreadsheets and ready-to-paste listing copy, generated alongside the assets.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="reveal">Why it's interesting engineering</h2>
  <ul class="reveal">
    <li><strong>Determinism.</strong> The same spec always produces the same output — covers and interiors are computed, not hand-placed, so a 102-page book and its 0.230" spine line up every time.</li>
    <li><strong>Leverage.</strong> Build cost per additional variant is effectively <strong>$0</strong>; the work was front-loaded into the generator.</li>
    <li><strong>Separation.</strong> Content spec, layout engine, and output format are decoupled, so a new product line is a new config — not a rewrite.</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="reveal"><em>This case study shows the generation system and its engineering. The specific products and storefronts it feeds are run as a separate, deliberately low-profile venture.</em></p>
</CaseStudy>
